## Section 1: The Navigation Matrix — Decongestion and Hierarchy

### 1.1 What the Screenshots Reveal

Across all six screenshots, the top navigation is the most consistently broken spatial zone. The nav contains three distinct layers of information — the brand mark ("CREÅTIVE STEEPING"), the Flavor Mode toggles (Incandescent, Oceanic, Emergent, Planetary, Dark Matter), and the portal link ("THE ÅLÏEN SCÖÕL ☰") — all attempting to coexist in a single horizontal strip that was designed for a 1280px desktop canvas.

On mobile, the result is a three-way collision. The Flavor Mode toggles, which are positioned absolutely at `left: 50%; transform: translateX(-50%)` in the desktop layout, do not reposition correctly at narrow widths. They overflow their container, clip against the brand mark on the left and the portal link on the right, and in some screenshots appear to wrap into a second row that pushes the nav height upward unpredictably.

The dropdown menus — "[ STEEPING NOTES ]", "[ THE STEEPERVERSE ]", "[ ME IN 5D ]", "[ BEGIN YOUR STEEP ]", "[ DISCORD PORTAL ]" — render as a large block that overlays primary content. In one screenshot, this dropdown sits directly over the "Who do I Think I Am?" headline and the "SONIC AWARENESS" panel simultaneously, making both inaccessible.

### 1.2 Root Cause: The Absolute Positioning Problem

The code inspection confirms the core issue. The `.mode-toggles` element uses `position: absolute; left: 50%; transform: translateX(-50%)` in the desktop layout. The existing mobile media query at `max-width: 768px` attempts to override this with `position: static !important; transform: none !important;` and moves the toggles to `order: 3` in the flex flow. However, the nav container itself does not have a defined `--navH` CSS variable resolved at mobile widths, meaning the `padding: var(--navH) var(--space-md)` rule on `.portal-screen` is computing against an undefined or zero value, collapsing the top padding that would otherwise create breathing room below the nav.

### 1.3 Responsive Design Directives for Navigation

The development team must treat the mobile navigation as a two-zone system: a **primary bar** (brand + hamburger trigger) and a **secondary layer** (Flavor Modes as a horizontal scroll strip). The portal dropdown must become a full-screen overlay.

| Element | Current Behavior on Mobile | Required Resolution |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Nav Container (`.top-nav`)** | Wraps unpredictably; height is auto but `--navH` is unresolved | Define `--navH` explicitly in the `@media (max-width: 768px)` block (e.g., `--navH: 100px`). Set `flex-direction: row; flex-wrap: wrap; align-items: center;` with a fixed `min-height`. |
| **Mode Toggles (`.mode-toggles`)** | Absolute positioning breaks; wraps into nav body | Remove absolute positioning entirely at mobile. Place toggles in a `width: 100%; overflow-x: auto; white-space: nowrap; -webkit-overflow-scrolling: touch;` horizontal scroll container as the second row of the nav. Hide the scrollbar via `::-webkit-scrollbar { display: none; }`. |
| **Brand Mark (`.nav-brand`)** | Correct, but font-size reduction to `0.8rem` makes it too small | Keep at `0.9rem` minimum. Ensure it anchors to `flex: 0 0 auto` so it never compresses. |
| **Portal Link / Dropdown (`.nav-school`)** | Dropdown overlays content | Convert to a full-screen overlay triggered by the ☰ icon. The overlay should use `position: fixed; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100vw; height: 100vh; z-index: 9999; background: var(--bg);` with a smooth `opacity` and `transform: translateY()` transition. |
| **"GUIDE TO THE STEEPERVERSE" nav item** | Wraps to multiple lines, collides with "RETURN TO VISCERAL EXPERIENCE" | These two items must never coexist in the same horizontal row on mobile. In the guide pages, the secondary nav strip should show only the current section label and a back arrow. |

