## Section 2: The Sonic Engine — Spatial Anchoring and Non-Obstruction

### 2.1 What the Screenshots Reveal

The Sonic Awareness panel (Engine: Soul Sonnet, Theremin toggle, Volume slider, Reading Lens) is currently a floating fixed-position widget anchored to the bottom-right corner. On mobile, it occupies approximately half the viewport width and sits at a `z-index` that places it over primary content. In one screenshot, it obscures the "Hfbgt." prompt and the "What is ready to be..." text entirely. In another, it overlaps with the "Active Pause" timers on the bottom-left, creating a visual collision between two equally important control systems.

The existing mobile CSS applies `transform: scale(0.85); transform-origin: right bottom;` to the `.sonic-engine-controls`, which reduces the widget slightly but does not solve the fundamental spatial conflict. The widget is still too large for a 390px canvas when expanded.

### 2.2 Spatial Logic: The Engine Must Breathe, Not Intrude

The Sonnet Engine is the heartbeat of the experience. Its controls are not secondary — they are environmental. But on mobile, environmental controls must be ambient, not dominant. The principle here is that a tight space forces the truth out, but it should not force the interface out of alignment. The controls must be present but not predatory.

### 2.3 Responsive Design Directives for the Sonic Engine

The development team should implement a **collapsible bottom drawer** pattern for the Sonic Awareness panel on mobile.

**Default (Collapsed) State:** A thin strip (approximately 48px tall) anchored to the bottom of the screen, showing only the current engine mode label (e.g., "SOUL SONNET") and a subtle animated waveform or pulse icon. This strip should be semi-transparent with a `backdrop-filter: blur(12px)` to remain legible against any background.

**Expanded State:** Tapping the strip slides the full panel upward using a `transform: translateY()` transition (approximately 300ms, `cubic-bezier(0.16, 1, 0.3, 1)`). The expanded panel should have a maximum height of `60vh` with `overflow-y: auto` to accommodate all controls without obscuring the primary content area.

**Active Pause Integration:** The Active Pause timers (5M, 15M, 22M) should be integrated into the same bottom bar ecosystem, positioned on the left side of the collapsed strip, so both time and sound controls share a single spatial zone at the bottom of the screen. This eliminates the bottom-left / bottom-right collision.

```css
/* Mobile Sonic Engine — Collapsed State */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .sonic-engine-controls {
    position: fixed;
    bottom: 0;
    left: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 48px;
    transform: none;
    transform-origin: unset;
    border-radius: 0;
    backdrop-filter: blur(12px);
    transition: height 0.3s cubic-bezier(0.16, 1, 0.3, 1);
    overflow: hidden;
  }

  .sonic-engine-controls.expanded {
    height: 60vh;
    overflow-y: auto;
  }

  .active-pause-container {
    position: fixed;
    bottom: 0;
    left: var(--space-md);
    transform: none;
    transform-origin: unset;
    height: 48px;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
  }
}
```

